    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Ghost in the Remote</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Amy Raffensperger letter on Randall Stross's May 7 column on proposed technology that could disable remote control during TV commercials</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Someone Has to Pay for TV. But Who? And How?'' (Digital Domain, May 7) in which Randall Stross discussed a proposed technology that could disable the remote control during commercials:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Someone Has to Pay for TV. But Who? And How?'' (Digital Domain, May 7) in which Randall Stross discussed a proposed technology that could disable the remote control during commercials:</p>
        <p>Since when is TV free? I and almost everyone I know pay for our television in either cable bills or satellite dish services. People who watch only broadcast television over the airwaves are few and far between. I will gladly keep my old VHS recorder and videotapes rather than submit to insipid and insulting commercials that ''pay'' for the television programming for which I already pay a very hefty monthly cable bill.</p>
        <p>If advertisers want my attention, all they have to do is make their commercials interesting. During the Super Bowl, I am much more interested in the commercials than in the actual game itself. If advertisers would use that kind of creativity year round, there would be no need for technology to make commercial viewing mandatory.</p>
        <p>Amy Raffensperger  Elizabethtown, Pa., May 9</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
